# Fluff Date: 2026-02-21 18:07:19
overview:<p>The Eyrie was introduced in 3087 as the first of Clan Jade Falcon's new generation of signature BattleMech designs. Weighing thirty-five tons, the Eyrie was designed as a versatile light striker capable of engaging opponents at range or in close quarters, filling a broader tactical niche than earlier Falcon light 'Mechs. Produced by Olivetti Weaponry at their facilities on Sudeten, the design was notable for incorporating melee combat features into a Clan chassis, a choice that signaled a shift in Jade Falcon military doctrine.</p><p>The Eyrie's striking raptor-like aesthetics, featuring upswept wings, a prominent beak-shaped cockpit, and legs armed with sharp talons, gave the design an immediately recognizable silhouette on the battlefield and reflected the Falcon identity its designers intended.</p>

capabilities:<p>Where the Cougar concentrates solely on firepower, the Eyrie focuses on greater mobility, heavier armor protection, and solid close-range offensive capability, making it suitable for a wider range of battlefield roles. Its Magna 210 XL engine drives the chassis to a respectable ninety-seven kilometers per hour, while the Olivetti S1 endo steel frame provides structural weight savings that allow for enhanced armor coverage. The 'Mech's distinctive partial wing serves a dual purpose, providing significant heat dissipation that allows the Eyrie to manage its thermal signature almost as quickly as it builds, while also extending the jump range of its Clan Standard Type A2 jets to approximately two hundred and ten meters.</p><p>The Eyrie's armament reflects its versatile combat philosophy. A pair of Type 3 Advanced Tactical Missile systems provide flexible engagement options across multiple range bands, while two Series 6a extended-range medium lasers deliver reliable damage at medium distances. For close-quarters engagements, four General Systems micro pulse lasers complement the 'Mech's leg-mounted talons, giving the Eyrie a devastating melee capability that few opponents expect from a Clan design. This combination of ranged flexibility and close-combat lethality makes the Eyrie a particularly dangerous opponent for other light 'Mechs, though its relatively thin armor remains a vulnerability against concentrated fire from heavier units, and the reliance on ammunition-dependent ATM launchers can leave the design exposed in prolonged engagements.</p>

deployment:<p>The Eyrie exists in a single production configuration, with no factory variants developed since its introduction. The baseline design pairs ranged missile and laser systems with dedicated close-combat hardware, positioning it as a versatile light 'Mech hunter and fast striker within Jade Falcon Clusters. The configuration has proven popular among recent sibko graduates and ristar warriors seeking to distinguish themselves, as its blend of engagement options rewards aggressive piloting and tactical creativity. Service has remained exclusive to Clan Jade Falcon, with other Clans and Inner Sphere powers showing little interest in adopting the design.</p>

history:<p>The Eyrie first saw combat during Clan Jade Falcon's attempt to claim the Lyran world of Zhongshan in 3087. The Second Falcon Jaegers made planetfall expecting to face the Thirteenth Wolf Guards, but instead found a mixed defensive force of Wolf garrison troops, mercenary commands, and planetary militia. During the opening engagements, a pair of Eyries tore through a platoon of militia armor with devastating effectiveness, closing to melee range and using their talons to shred the enemy 'Mechs' legs. A subsequent engagement pitted the same two machines against a Pack Hunter and a Wolfhound, with the Eyries crippling both opponents through aggressive outmaneuvering and close-range firepower. Although the Jade Falcons ultimately failed to take Zhongshan, the Eyrie had proven its worth, and the design quickly proliferated throughout other Falcon Clusters.</p><p>The Eyrie's reputation as a common choice for recent sibko graduates and ristar warriors seeking to prove themselves has given the design a distinctive place within Jade Falcon military culture. Its melee capability, once considered radical, became an accepted part of Falcon tactical doctrine, paving the way for later designs that incorporated similar close-combat features.</p><p>Despite nearly sixty years of consistent combat usage, the Eyrie has remained in service solely with Clan Jade Falcon. Other Clans have generally eschewed the design, viewing it as a Falcon totem 'Mech and considering it inherently inferior by association. Inner Sphere opponents, particularly those from the Lyran Commonwealth Armed Forces and the Republic Armed Forces, developed a negative perception of the Eyrie, most Lyran or Republic MechWarriors who downed one tended to strip it for usable parts and abandon the chassis rather than claim it as salvage. Only non-Clan warriors willing to overlook its faction associations would typically claim a functioning Eyrie for their own use.</p><p>The Eyrie's design influence extended beyond its own chassis, serving as the aesthetic template for later Jade Falcon 'Mechs developed during the Clan's revitalization programs of the thirty-second century. Designs such as the Gyrfalcon and the Shrike shared the distinctive wing styling that first appeared on the Eyrie, establishing a visual identity for an entire generation of Falcon military hardware.</p>

